{"term":"1973","caseName":"Merrill Lynch, Pierce, Fenner & Smith, Inc. v. Ware","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1973/72-312","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - October 10, 1973","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/16763","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Barton, you may continue, you have 15 minutes left.","start":0,"stop":6.279,"duration":6.28}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the court.","start":6.279,"stop":9.467,"duration":3.19},{"text":"I believe at the conclusion of yesterday's session, the Court had addressed itself to the 6 (c) argument concerning the application of state law.","start":9.467,"stop":20.122,"duration":10.66},{"text":"In that connection, I would like to point out to the Court that the Securities and Exchange Commission in their amicus brief files in the osmosis of the Solicitor General considered that very argument made by the petitioner, and stated on Page 9 of its brief that there is no basis for suggesting that Rule 347 (b) was required to implement the literal language of the act or any commission rule.","start":20.122,"stop":50.379,"duration":30.26},{"text":"It further concluded that the application of California law was proper in this case and urged affirmance of the California court decision.","start":50.379,"stop":60.854,"duration":10.48},{"text":"I would like to point out regarding Section 6 (c) that it specifically provides that any rule enacted by any exchange must conform to the the rules and regulations of the Securities Exchange Act as well as the rules and regulations of the Securities and Exchange Commission and that this Court has held in Silver v. New York Stock Exchange that the rule of an exchange may be judicially invalidated as being beyond the great purposes of the Securities Exchange Act.","start":60.854,"stop":100.364,"duration":39.51},{"text":"I submit that rule, that 28 (c) and Rule 347 (b) as adopted by the New York Stock Exchange is a stipulation, that's in the meaning of Section 78 CCA of the Act and is void by reason there of.","start":100.364,"stop":123.274,"duration":22.91},{"text":"Moreover, it is inconsistent with the grant of judicial authority that Congress gave the courts in Section 27 of the Act which would be 15 U.S.C. 78aa and that provides that the District Courts of the United States shall have exclusive jurisdiction of violations of this chapter with the rules and regulations they are under.","start":123.274,"stop":147.285,"duration":24.01},{"text":"In addition, Rule 347 (b) is inconsistent with the provisions of the Federal Arbitration Act, since admittedly, it is an agreement which concerns interstate commerce and which is a part of the employment contract.","start":147.285,"stop":163.73,"duration":16.44},{"text":"As this Court noted in the Prima Paint decision, the Federal Arbitration Act was not meant to apply to contracts of employment between parties of an equal bargaining strength.","start":163.73,"stop":176.95,"duration":13.22},{"text":"Justice Black in his dissenting opinion in that case spelled out the legislative intent behind the Federal Arbitration Act, and that was that it was not meant to apply to contracts of employment.","start":176.95,"stop":191.749,"duration":14.8},{"text":"Now both this Court and Silver and the Senate Subcommittee, the Securities -- the Subcommittee on Securities in its extensive analysis of the functioning of the New York Stock Exchange concluded that judicial review was necessary regarding the self regulatory powers of the New York Stock Exchange.","start":191.749,"stop":213.144,"duration":21.4},{"text":"I would like to observe at this point that it is not the New York Stock Exchange which is a party to this lawsuit but rather a private corporation that came into existence by virtue of state law and that Merrill Lynch, like being a member of the0 New York Stock Exchange is also a member of the Pacific Coast Stock Exchange which is physically located in California.","start":213.144,"stop":244.004,"duration":30.86},{"text":"Now if Congress meant physical location in Section 6 c, it would lead to disunity in decision because there are many stock exchanges located throughout the country which are not in New York and that would give a stock exchange moreover, the opportunity to physically locate itself in a state whose laws are favorable to its policies and thereby effectively emasculate the laws of 49 other states.","start":244.004,"stop":278.085,"duration":34.08}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"You are suggesting then that if Pacific Coast Exchange had a rule like the New York Stock Exchange does, it could not enforce it under Merrill Lynch's theory because it is physically located in California?","start":278.085,"stop":290.795,"duration":12.71}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I submit that would be correct under one rationale.","start":290.795,"stop":294.889,"duration":4.09},{"text":"I believe that Congress intended, by location to mean the application of those laws of a state which have significant interest in the case, such as California in this case.","start":294.889,"stop":309.619,"duration":14.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The Pacific Stock Exchange had any rules touching this area of relationship between a termination of employment of a registered customers plan or employer?","start":309.619,"stop":323.242,"duration":13.62}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, the Pacific Coast Stock Exchange does have rules concerning arbitration which are very similar to Article 8, Section 1 of the New York Stock Exchange Constitution which provides in essence that a member, Merrill Lynch in this case cannot compel beyond member to arbitrate.","start":323.242,"stop":344.221,"duration":20.98},{"text":"That choice is given to the non-member, if he willingly wishes to invoke arbitration and the rationale behind that distinction is that obviously Merrill Lynch has voice in the exchange rules which an employee does not have, so they do not have equal bargaining strength.","start":344.221,"stop":361.457,"duration":17.24},{"text":"So they give the non-number the option to request arbitration.","start":361.457,"stop":367.584,"duration":6.13}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think the Federal Court should order arbitration in a case like is now before us if the employee demands it?","start":367.584,"stop":377.616,"duration":10.03}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"If the employee demands it?","start":377.616,"stop":380.44,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Under California law?","start":380.44,"stop":382.401,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me, Your Honor.","start":382.401,"stop":383.185,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Under California law?","start":383.185,"stop":384.449,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think that if the employee demands it that would be an exception.","start":384.449,"stop":389.798,"duration":5.35},{"text":"The application would be--","start":389.798,"stop":390.464,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It would be a waiver, I suppose, of the California law?","start":390.464,"stop":393.285,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Section 229 of the California Labor Code.","start":393.285,"stop":396.115,"duration":2.83},{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":396.115,"stop":396.986,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"You have no difficulty with this waving and provision that was made for his benefit in this context of employer-employee relationship?","start":396.986,"stop":406.976,"duration":9.99}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Is Your Honor referring to the arbitration process?","start":406.976,"stop":408.699,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":408.699,"stop":410.001,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, it is not my opinion that the arbitration clause of the rule was made for the benefit the employee but rather to benefit the members of the New York Stock Exchange because the employee would be compelled to arbitrate before what I consider a less than impartial panel.","start":410.001,"stop":426.503,"duration":16.5}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you speaking of the California law that you were engaged in the colloquy talk with Mr. Justice Stewart waiving the benefits of the California's statute?","start":426.503,"stop":438.135,"duration":11.63},{"text":"You have no difficulty with this waiving that?","start":438.135,"stop":439.382,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Well, Your Honor.","start":439.382,"stop":440.705,"duration":1.32},{"text":"When there is a -- I was to say, a body of decision that indicates that an individual may not waive a law inactive for his benefit, that represents public policy.","start":440.705,"stop":453.502,"duration":12.8},{"text":"I would say that the California courts would have to consider in a factual context whether or not --.","start":453.502,"stop":460.495,"duration":6.99}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Then I misunderstood you because I thought you told Justice Stewart in response to his question that he could waive it?","start":460.495,"stop":467.164,"duration":6.67}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the employee could waive it, Your Honor, but whether the California courts would recognize that waiver is a different question.","start":467.164,"stop":475.964,"duration":8.8},{"text":"And I should also point out that Rule 347 (b) does conflict.","start":475.964,"stop":480.895,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't follow that.","start":480.895,"stop":483.099,"duration":2.2},{"text":"If I understand, if I read Section 29 correctly, what it says is that the individual may maintain an action without regard to the existence of any file being arbitrated.","start":483.099,"stop":494.54,"duration":11.44},{"text":"However, the employee didn't bother bringing an action, but rather submitted the arbitration with probably the California courts have ever get to?","start":494.54,"stop":504.328,"duration":9.79}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"In that context, Your Honor, they would not, unless the employer moves the court to compel that the matter not be arbitrated but go to court.","start":504.328,"stop":515.011,"duration":10.68}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Each of the arbitration was completed, the employee might be then making collateral attack or other attack on the arbitration plan?","start":515.011,"stop":525.391,"duration":10.38}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"That is not permitted under California law, Your Honor.","start":525.391,"stop":528.084,"duration":2.69},{"text":"It is the --.","start":528.084,"stop":528.592,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we said we could not get there in any other way, it might get there if he brought section accurate in the court?","start":528.592,"stop":534.634,"duration":6.04}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct Your Honor.","start":534.634,"stop":536.492,"duration":1.86},{"text":"If the employees submitted to arbitration, and the employer rejected that request, the employer would then be in the position of going to court to avoid arbitration, the issue that would arise in that context, and I guess it could also rise in the context where both parties have submitted the arbitration and then after the arbitration, a word was made the employee being dissatisfied with it, would petition the courts.","start":536.492,"stop":568.977,"duration":32.49},{"text":"But under that circumstance, Your Honor, the Californian courts would not consider that objection as I understand existing California law.","start":568.977,"stop":579.839,"duration":10.86},{"text":"I should also --.","start":579.839,"stop":580.743,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Once, once he voluntarily goes to arbitrations, he can't take advantage of 229 rather?","start":580.743,"stop":586.848,"duration":6.1}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor.","start":586.848,"stop":587.611,"duration":0.76},{"text":"He is bound, by since 229, as the states on this space is not compulsory.","start":587.611,"stop":593.382,"duration":5.77},{"text":"It does not say must.","start":593.382,"stop":594.772,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It may be maintained.","start":594.772,"stop":595.78,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":595.78,"stop":595.946,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Without regard to current requirement.","start":595.946,"stop":598.32,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr Barton, is this motion to arbitrate that the petitioner filed in response to your complaint in the superior court, is that an independent proceeding under California law or is it just a part of the defense raised to your claim for wages?","start":598.32,"stop":617.272,"duration":18.95}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, under California law it could be either an independent action or it could be part of a lawsuit.","start":617.272,"stop":626.46,"duration":9.19},{"text":"There are situations arising under California law where you may go in the court on just a petition to arbitrate.","start":626.46,"stop":633.628,"duration":7.17}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"But that wasn't what happened.","start":633.628,"stop":634.868,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"That is not what happened.","start":634.868,"stop":636.17,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"And actually the decision of the Court of Appeal isn't a final disposition of this case, is it?","start":636.17,"stop":642.162,"duration":5.99}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor under California law it isn't.","start":642.162,"stop":646.757,"duration":4.59},{"text":"It established the law of the cases for the legality of the forfeiture provision.","start":646.757,"stop":651.015,"duration":4.26},{"text":"That is the Court of Appeals indicated there are other issues that remain to be decided by the Trial court.","start":651.015,"stop":656.86,"duration":5.85}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"And if the California Court of Appeal disposition were followed here, the case would go back to the superior Court for Trial to the Court on your client's compliant.","start":656.86,"stop":667.25,"duration":10.39}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor.","start":667.25,"stop":670.041,"duration":2.79},{"text":"However, in all fairness, I should note that if the court consider arbitration to be an outcome determinative, as was indicated in the Bernhard decision, then that part of the California decision would be final.","start":670.041,"stop":686.271,"duration":16.23},{"text":"I should also like to know Your Honor that if I understood counsel's opening argument, he indicated that the profit-sharing plan by virtue of Article 18.1, which is noted at page 41 Appendix, specifically stated the profit-sharing plan was not to be construed as part of the employment contract, and I submit under that theory then Rule 347(b) would have no application in this case, because it specifically relates to employment disputes.","start":686.271,"stop":721.596,"duration":35.33},{"text":"And by the functioning of Article 18.1, it would be excluded from the application of Rule 347(b).","start":721.596,"stop":731.841,"duration":10.25},{"text":"Now concerning Counsel's statement that respondents -- some have been guilty of forum shopping, I submit that is not accurate.","start":731.841,"stop":743.674,"duration":11.83},{"text":"Now each and every respondent is a citizen or resident of the state of California.","start":743.674,"stop":750.359,"duration":6.69},{"text":"All they have done is petitioned their own state courts or decision regarding this dispute.","start":750.359,"stop":756.244,"duration":5.88},{"text":"They have not sought to go outside their home state, for example Nevada or Wyoming to forum shop.","start":756.244,"stop":764.11,"duration":7.87},{"text":"This is not a case of forum shopping.","start":764.11,"stop":768.748,"duration":4.64},{"text":"Now the policy of California is spelled out in several cases.","start":768.748,"stop":774.727,"duration":5.98},{"text":"California courts deemed in a matter of important strong public policy considering the right of the wager into to all lawfully approved wages.","start":774.727,"stop":784.379,"duration":9.65},{"text":"In this context, I would like to note that although technically Merrill Lynch made all contributions to the profit-sharing plans, those contributions evolved because of the work and labor of the employees, who contributed to the profit of Merrill Lynch, and it is no different than Merrill Lynch writing out a check to Mr, Ware or any other respondent for their weekly wages because profit-sharing even as interpreted by Federal Court, results because of a man's labor and is not construed as a gift.","start":784.379,"stop":823.835,"duration":39.46},{"text":"Now, the concern of the Courts to avoid forfeitures has manifested I think most recently by the action of the senate in adopting and passing HR4200, which is the private pension plan will, and that states no unequivocal terms that to qualify under the Internal Revenue Code, a pension may not contain a forfeiture provision.","start":823.835,"stop":852.929,"duration":29.09},{"text":"It also provides that an individual works and is given retirement benefits can carry those benefits from employer to employee, excuse me to employer.","start":852.929,"stop":865.592,"duration":12.66},{"text":"Now this is more or less a parallel to profit-sharing, it shows the great concern not only in the state courts but in Congress that may not be deprived of his lawfully approved benefits and that he be paid them.","start":865.592,"stop":883.317,"duration":17.73},{"text":"Now I submit --","start":883.317,"stop":884.309,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You still would have a stronger case, if it were a contributory plan, wouldn't you?","start":884.309,"stop":890.469,"duration":6.16}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor that's really kind of theoretical question, because if David Ware and the rest of the respondents didn't work and contribute to Merrill Lynch's profit they wouldn't get paid anything.","start":890.469,"stop":901.644,"duration":11.17}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Merrill Lynch probably views, this is a gratuity on their part, it's something that deals with loyalty or two sides to the issues.","start":901.644,"stop":908.485,"duration":6.84}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, I would agree to that Your Honor.","start":908.485,"stop":912.494,"duration":4.01},{"text":"I don't make that distinction though between --","start":912.494,"stop":914.875,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in any event, that really goes to the merits of what would be tried in a court.","start":914.875,"stop":920.926,"duration":6.05},{"text":"if you are correct or tried by an arbitrator, if your brother on the other side is correct.","start":920.926,"stop":930.047,"duration":9.12},{"text":"There is no question, but isn't it conceded that these are wages and that's what the statute says --","start":930.047,"stop":936.109,"duration":6.06}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":936.109,"stop":936.705,"duration":0.6},{"text":"Petitioner concedes that.","start":936.705,"stop":937.818,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think there was any question.","start":937.818,"stop":938.94,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"There isn't.","start":938.94,"stop":940.102,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"In the Trial on the merits, what is your idea of scope of the issues that will be covered, will they include for example, any claim that there was a breach of the fiduciary duty, is that open?","start":940.102,"stop":954.333,"duration":14.23}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I believe that Merrill Lynch will make such a claim.","start":954.333,"stop":960.511,"duration":6.18}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"That's open to be tried out there.","start":960.511,"stop":962.928,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, if there is a breach of a fiduciary duty.","start":962.928,"stop":965.865,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Taking customer's lists and that sort of thing.","start":965.865,"stop":968.547,"duration":2.68},{"text":"If they can establish --.","start":968.547,"stop":970.088,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, as against each individual employee or former employee.","start":970.088,"stop":976.921,"duration":6.83},{"text":"That would be one of the issues that I believe the Court of Appeals in California left open.","start":976.921,"stop":982.956,"duration":6.03},{"text":"So obviously Merrill Lynch's rights are not prejudiced by having trial.","start":982.956,"stop":989.424,"duration":6.47},{"text":"One trial I should note Your Honor that would include everyone in the class and to decide at one time and for all time, what the respective rights of the parties are.","start":989.424,"stop":1001.688,"duration":12.26},{"text":"Now on the opposite side of the coin, we have Merrill Lynch suggesting that it would be more efficient and effective to have 90, 100 or more separate arbitration hearings to decide each case individually, and as the court knows there is no principle such as stare decisis that binds arbitrators; a group of arbitrators could decide one case one way, could decide the next case the other way.","start":1001.688,"stop":1031.776,"duration":30.09},{"text":"It is not a necessary calvary of arbitration under the New York Stock Exchange Plan that one panel of arbitrators would hear each and every one of those cases.","start":1031.776,"stop":1043.373,"duration":11.6}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any indication of why your state Court of Appeals finished its course by 183 --","start":1043.373,"stop":1051.873,"duration":8.5}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, there is Your Honor.","start":1051.873,"stop":1053.804,"duration":1.93},{"text":"And the case was presented Frame versus Merrill Lynch, the Labor Code, Section 229 argument was not made, neither it was there an explication of the effectiveness of Rule 347(b) in relationship, for example, to the New York Stock Exchange constitutional, waived.","start":1053.804,"stop":1079.949,"duration":26.14},{"text":"In the exhibits for this Court, after oral argument before the Court of Appeals; the issue of Frame v. Merrill Lynch came up.","start":1079.949,"stop":1094.292,"duration":14.34},{"text":"Thereafter, the court send a letter to respective counsel which is exhibit D requesting --","start":1094.292,"stop":1102.597,"duration":8.31}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it the Appendix?","start":1102.597,"stop":1103.997,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"No it's not the Appendix Your Honor, it's only exhibits.","start":1103.997,"stop":1107.387,"duration":3.39},{"text":"It's exhibit D requesting further written argument regarding five separate points.","start":1107.387,"stop":1116.792,"duration":9.4},{"text":"One of those points was related to Labor Code Section 229.","start":1116.792,"stop":1126.309,"duration":9.52},{"text":"The Court specifically held in Ware versus Merrill Lynch, that the Court didn't consider the application of Frame versus Merrill Lynch of Labor Code Section 229 and I think the court should be commended for having a judicial courage to reverse what I considered an incorrect decision at the outset and I should also know that under the class aspects of this case that Mr. Frame, I believe would be covered.","start":1126.309,"stop":1164.845,"duration":38.54}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though he lost?","start":1164.845,"stop":1166.236,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well he didn't lose against merits, Your Honor.","start":1166.236,"stop":1168.206,"duration":1.97},{"text":"All it said was that, there should be arbitration and I believe --","start":1168.206,"stop":1171.544,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's on the merits of the issue, it's not before us.","start":1171.544,"stop":1173.845,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1173.845,"stop":1174.532,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the issue as.","start":1174.532,"stop":1175.569,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"well I should note that that is the issue of arbitration.","start":1175.569,"stop":1178.972,"duration":3.4},{"text":"I should note that there was an extensive discussion between myself and Mr. Frame's counsel regarding his position before the argument on appeal and there was an invitation at that time extended to him to join in the class and of course we considered in great detail, what decision he was going to take in his briefs which was different from the position that I took on behalf the quest in my brief.","start":1178.972,"stop":1210.831,"duration":31.86},{"text":"I believe, Your Honor in conclusion that I would like to know that -- I just feel of it inconceivable what Congress could have meant that New York law which has no significant context with California residents in this case should apply to the exclusion of Law -- 49 other states many of which would have significant context as far as their own residents are concerned at least.","start":1210.831,"stop":1238.468,"duration":27.64}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this is not correct.","start":1238.468,"stop":1239.383,"duration":0.91},{"text":"It is merely the issue, is it.","start":1239.383,"stop":1241.531,"duration":2.15},{"text":"It isn't the real issue whether this rule of the New York Stock Exchange declined which incorporates or refers to New York Law, but it's a rule of the New York Stock--","start":1241.531,"stop":1251.579,"duration":10.05}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1251.579,"stop":1253.689,"duration":2.11},{"text":"Pursuant to it's rule making authority granted under 6(c).","start":1253.689,"stop":1256.639,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1256.639,"stop":1260.568,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"If there are no further questions, I would like to thank the court this time.","start":1260.568,"stop":1265.027,"duration":4.46}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Barton.","start":1265.027,"stop":1266.235,"duration":1.21},{"text":"Mr. Orrick.","start":1266.235,"stop":1269.759,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice.","start":1269.759,"stop":1270.826,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Orrick, at some point would you mind dealing with the Government's argument in 6 © -- the language of 6 (c) is very broad, any rule it says, any rule but I read the brief amicus of the Securities And Exchange commission is saying no, any rule should be limited to rules related to investor protection, fair dealing or fair exchange administration.","start":1270.826,"stop":1301.223,"duration":30.4},{"text":"I gather based on, what they give us in the way of legislative history of 6 (c) and of the general purposes of the Act and as I read their conclusion, it is that any rule does not embrace 347 (b).","start":1301.223,"stop":1315.112,"duration":13.89}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir and with that I take exception, the legislative history or the Act is replete with discussions of the deficiencies in employees of the securities industry both as to their competence and to their integrity.","start":1315.112,"stop":1334.353,"duration":19.24},{"text":"So even the 1964 special study mandated by Congress, I had similar references to these deficiencies and indeed if the court would look at the agreements made by Mr. Ware and his colleagues and I call attention to them, one at question here which is on Page 8 of the Appendix to our brief, it's the sub-section J, Rule 345 and it reads English is as plain as it can be written, I agree that any controversy between me and any member or member organization or affiliate or subsidy there, arising out of my employment or the termination of my employment shall be settled by arbitration at the instance of any such party in accordance with the arbitration procedure prescribed in the constitution and rule then obtained at the New York Stock Exchange and then if you read Mr. Ware's affidavit which appears in Volume 1 of the record at page 171 and he says, as far as I knew, this was nothing more than an application for registration at no time with provisions contained in that form discussed with me or explained to me, nor was I ever provided with any sort of study guide, referencing the provisions before I signed it.","start":1334.353,"stop":1429.002,"duration":94.65},{"text":"I didn't understand it to be a contract or agreement of any type.","start":1429.002,"stop":1433.345,"duration":4.34},{"text":"I suggest that this record itself is reason enough for the Securities and Exchange Commission to regulate the conduct of employees.","start":1433.345,"stop":1448.308,"duration":14.96},{"text":"Here are these employees who are dealing with -- giving financial advice to widows and orphans who will say under oath if they don't understand what they read and back out on their agreements.","start":1448.308,"stop":1462.559,"duration":14.25}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Orrick, is there anything in the record indicating whether Ware was also a member of the Pacific Coast Exchange as a result of his employment with Merrill Lynch?","start":1462.559,"stop":1472.241,"duration":9.68}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't recall if there is anything in record on that.","start":1472.241,"stop":1476.392,"duration":4.15},{"text":"Now, the position of Merill Lynch is first, we have an agreement to arbitrate under a rule of the New York Stock Exchange which is valid in the state of New York and under 6 (c) that rule should be adhered to, whatever veneer, the SEC can put on the rule by saying that this is within our oversight, the purview of our oversight simply enforces the status of this rule which we claim here has the--","start":1476.392,"stop":1521.04,"duration":44.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But am I right Mr. Orrick that your whole case depends on 6 (c), the language of 6 ©, rules and regulation including 347 (b), doesn't it.","start":1521.04,"stop":1536.481,"duration":15.44}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now the whole case is – yesterday, I said first, we have a right to arbitration under the California Arbitration Act which is the same as the Federal Arbitration Act.","start":1536.481,"stop":1551.921,"duration":15.44},{"text":"We have a right to arbitration under these--","start":1551.921,"stop":1554.443,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But that's not a federal question, that's not our problem.","start":1554.443,"stop":1557.763,"duration":3.32},{"text":"So far as your case in this court turns on your persuading us, does it not that 6 (c) covers 347 (b)?","start":1557.763,"stop":1566.39,"duration":8.63}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well the 347 (b) was enacted pursuant to--","start":1566.39,"stop":1571.799,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"A rule and regulation within 6 ©.","start":1571.799,"stop":1575.638,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I think it's also a rule and regulation enacted pursuant to Article 3, Section 6 of the New York Stock Exchange and it is an equally valid binding agreement.","start":1575.638,"stop":1591.073,"duration":15.44},{"text":"What we have here is an agreement to arbitrate.","start":1591.073,"stop":1594.866,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that, what's Article 6, Section 3?","start":1594.866,"stop":1597.527,"duration":2.66},{"text":"Where is that?","start":1597.527,"stop":1598.34,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Article 3, Section 6, I don't believe that we have it printed.","start":1598.34,"stop":1602.767,"duration":4.43},{"text":"It's in the constitution of the New York Stock Exchange which authorizes the directors to make such rules and regulations as are necessary.","start":1602.767,"stop":1614.455,"duration":11.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Listening to part of your argument, it is certainly related to 6 (c) argument, the California rule sets it not an important objective of the Federal Law.","start":1614.455,"stop":1625.256,"duration":10.8}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly sir.","start":1625.256,"stop":1626.801,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And wholly aside from 6 (c) you would argue that?","start":1626.801,"stop":1629.616,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1629.616,"stop":1629.999,"duration":0.38},{"text":"An important federal policy.","start":1629.999,"stop":1631.434,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't need to argue that expect in connection with 6, if you have read about it, 6 (c) automatically picks it--","start":1631.434,"stop":1638.425,"duration":6.99}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I am trying to say, the rules such as--","start":1638.425,"stop":1643.608,"duration":5.18}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"What is that important Federal policy?","start":1643.608,"stop":1645.449,"duration":1.84},{"text":"Is it uniformity or is it preference for arbitration?","start":1645.449,"stop":1650.77,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The New York Stock Exchange and the securities industry has a federally mandated, self-regulation in order to accomplish this self-regulation as Judge Medina has indicated in the (Inaudible) case.","start":1650.77,"stop":1670.356,"duration":19.59},{"text":"Necessary element of it is to be able to enforce arbitration and if you are unable to enforce the arbitration, which is guarded with respect to a rule governing the conduct of employees in one state or you can do it in another state, I think that defies the very purpose of this federally mandated self-regulation.","start":1670.356,"stop":1701.814,"duration":31.46}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah if New York were to change its law tomorrow, so that its law were the same is California's.","start":1701.814,"stop":1707.744,"duration":5.93},{"text":"Under your theory, that arbitration rule couldn't be enforced anywhere?","start":1707.744,"stop":1712.072,"duration":4.33}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think to be fair with the board I think if New York had a rule 229, we would have a different case.","start":1712.072,"stop":1721.83,"duration":9.76},{"text":"That is not our case here, however.","start":1721.83,"stop":1724.48,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Well so, so New York can set it not as important Federal preference for arbitration under your own theory.","start":1724.48,"stop":1733.338,"duration":8.86}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think that is so, yes.","start":1733.338,"stop":1739.459,"duration":6.12}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose Mr. Orrick, if New York had a 229 then section -- Section c would rule out the arbitration provision of the New York Stock Exchange because the only rules that the Exchange may adopt are rules and regulations not inconsistent with the applicable laws of the state which is located.","start":1739.459,"stop":1761.901,"duration":22.44},{"text":"So, if New York had a 229 that would nullify, would it not, the arbitration provisions of 347 (b)?","start":1761.901,"stop":1770.075,"duration":8.17}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1770.075,"stop":1770.82,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless, the commission is self required by regulation?","start":1770.82,"stop":1778.363,"duration":7.54}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"One other point I want to make Justice Rehnquist, ask Mr. Barton as to whether or not that California court order is final, it is indeed final as to Merrill Lynch where the petition to arbitrate is denied.","start":1778.363,"stop":1800.622,"duration":22.26}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"This was something you raised as a defense when you were brought into court by Mr. Barton' client, isn't it?","start":1800.622,"stop":1809.513,"duration":8.89},{"text":"It wasn't a separate action that you brought to compel arbitration.","start":1809.513,"stop":1813.49,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We filed in effect that what we did, we filed an answer and we filed a petition to arbitrate and the court denied the petition to arbitrate and that's what was on appeal.","start":1813.49,"stop":1835.36,"duration":21.87},{"text":"With respect to the question that Justice Stewart asked, Mr. Barton asked whether or not Section 229 was part of the Frame case, he asked if there is any explanation for these two diametrically opposite opinions.","start":1835.36,"stop":1855.783,"duration":20.42},{"text":"Mr. Barton correctly said that it wasn't discussed in the Frame case but it was briefed in the Frame case.","start":1855.783,"stop":1866.71,"duration":10.93},{"text":"It didn't take part in the opinion.","start":1866.71,"stop":1872,"duration":5.29}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Orrick, thank you Mr. Barton.","start":1872,"stop":1874.359,"duration":2.36},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":1874.359,"stop":1875.948,"duration":1.59}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - October 09, 1973","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/17355","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We will hear arguments next in Merrill Lynch against David Ware.","start":0,"stop":28.933,"duration":28.93},{"text":"Mr. Orrick you may proceed whenever you are ready.","start":28.933,"stop":32.085,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and members of the court.","start":32.085,"stop":35.853,"duration":3.77},{"text":"With the permission of the court, I would like to save my last 10 minutes for rebuttal.","start":35.853,"stop":41.367,"duration":5.51},{"text":"This case is here on a writ of certiorari to the First Appellate District of the Court Of Appeal Of California which is our intermediate Appellate Court.","start":41.367,"stop":52.336,"duration":10.97},{"text":"It is an action for declaratory relief and damages which was brought in the California Superior Court by Mr. Ware on behalf of himself and others alleging that a forfeiture provision in a profit sharing plan violated by California Law and is unenforcible.","start":52.336,"stop":73.42,"duration":21.08},{"text":"Merrill Lynch answered and petitioned for arbitration and it did so because it had agreed with Merrill Lynch, with Ware, that any and all disputes arising out of his employment would be arbitrated in accordance with the rules of New York Stock Exchange.","start":73.42,"stop":96.074,"duration":22.65},{"text":"The Judge in the Superior Court denied the petition without findings and he was affirmed by the Court of Appeal.","start":96.074,"stop":110.579,"duration":14.5},{"text":"Not withstanding the fact that four months prior, the very same court had held under identical facts that Merrill Lynch had the right to arbitrate.","start":110.579,"stop":122.189,"duration":11.61},{"text":"Now that case is the Ware case which we have included in our Appendix and to which I shall make further reference.","start":122.189,"stop":134.457,"duration":12.27},{"text":"Merrill Lynch then petitioned the Supreme Court of California to review these two conflicting decisions.","start":134.457,"stop":141.642,"duration":7.19},{"text":"The Supreme Court denied it and we came here to ascertain whether or not there isn't a federal interest in maintaining the uniform application of these New York Stock Exchange rules.","start":141.642,"stop":162.523,"duration":20.88},{"text":"Now the pertinent facts are few and they can be stated simply.","start":162.523,"stop":170.248,"duration":7.72},{"text":"Ware was employed as an Account Executive at Merrill Lynch in July 1958.","start":170.248,"stop":179.446,"duration":9.2},{"text":"Merrill Lynch is a member of the New York Stock Exchange and as such it is required to abide by its rules which include the fact that all account executives must be registered representatives of the Stock Exchange.","start":179.446,"stop":198.091,"duration":18.65},{"text":"Now, to become a registered representative of the Stock Exchange, it is necessary for the applicant to undergo a rigorous 26 week training course to pass an examination with respect to both his competence and his integrity and then he must agree to abide by the rules of the New York Stock Exchange.","start":198.091,"stop":227.306,"duration":29.22},{"text":"The rules requiring are set forth in the appendix to our brief, Rule 345 and the rules governing arbitration, Rule 347 is on page 9 of the appendix.","start":227.306,"stop":245.669,"duration":18.36},{"text":"Mr. Ware did exactly this.","start":245.669,"stop":248.114,"duration":2.44},{"text":"He took the course, he passed and he signed an agreement to abide by the rules of the New York Stock Exchange.","start":248.114,"stop":256.112,"duration":8}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me Mr. Orrick.","start":256.112,"stop":257.195,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir?","start":257.195,"stop":257.906,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"The other case you refer to is Frame.","start":257.906,"stop":259.971,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Frame excuse me yes.","start":259.971,"stop":261.666,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"And I gather -- both I understand it from Division four, is that right?","start":261.666,"stop":267.589,"duration":5.92}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":267.589,"stop":268.368,"duration":0.78},{"text":"They were both the same division.","start":268.368,"stop":270.532,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"That is First Appellate District.","start":270.532,"stop":272.272,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The First Appellate District.","start":272.272,"stop":273.561,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"And at least one judge was common to both panels.","start":273.561,"stop":276.615,"duration":3.05}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":276.615,"stop":277.188,"duration":0.57},{"text":"Judge (Inaudible), yes sir; that's correct.","start":277.188,"stop":281.77,"duration":4.58}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"And we decided it months apart.","start":281.77,"stop":283.697,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Four months apart.","start":283.697,"stop":284.561,"duration":0.86},{"text":"Yes sir.","start":284.561,"stop":286.668,"duration":2.11},{"text":"The Frame then went to work as a registered representative in San Fransisco office of Merrill Lynch.","start":286.668,"stop":299.939,"duration":13.27}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Ware or Frame?","start":299.939,"stop":302.114,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I spoke myself.","start":302.114,"stop":303.943,"duration":1.83},{"text":"Thank you Mr. Justice.","start":303.943,"stop":306.546,"duration":2.6},{"text":"This is Ware case.","start":306.546,"stop":310.192,"duration":3.65},{"text":"He then went to work for Merrill Lynch and he became eligible in January, to become a participant in the Merrill Lynch profit-sharing plan.","start":310.192,"stop":322.025,"duration":11.83},{"text":"Now the Merrill Lynch profit-sharing plan is a plan which Merrill Lynch is a sole contributor.","start":322.025,"stop":330.083,"duration":8.06},{"text":"And the purpose of the plan is to provide an incentive for the employee to stay with Merrill Lynch and to provide him a future and additional source of income.","start":330.083,"stop":345.395,"duration":15.31}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you regard both of these aspects that is the arbitration clause and the retirement clause as part of the contractual arrangement?","start":345.395,"stop":356.211,"duration":10.82}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":356.211,"stop":358.455,"duration":2.24},{"text":"The plan specifically provides an Article 18, that it is not be considered part of the contract.","start":358.455,"stop":367.222,"duration":8.77}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"The arbitration clause is.","start":367.222,"stop":368.951,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The arbitration clause is.","start":368.951,"stop":372.141,"duration":3.19},{"text":"The plan has several other very important provisions.","start":372.141,"stop":379.696,"duration":7.56},{"text":"In Section 22.1, it provides that it shall be interpreted under the laws of New York and in Article 11.1 which brings about the instant lawsuit.","start":379.696,"stop":398.397,"duration":18.7},{"text":"It provides that an employee voluntarily terminates his employment with Merrill Lynch and goes to work for a competitor that his rights and benefits under the plan, maybe declared forfeit.","start":398.397,"stop":423.558,"duration":25.16},{"text":"Now to join the plan Mr. Ware had to agree that the conditions of the plan and this he did, his second agreement.","start":423.558,"stop":433.766,"duration":10.21}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Orrick, why is it important in your argument that the contract provider should be interpreted according to the laws of New York?","start":433.766,"stop":442.436,"duration":8.67}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Because what appeared to be the gravamen of Mr. Ware's action, namely, that the Business and Professions Code Section 16,600, made this forfeiture clause invalid, and therefore the choice of law -- therefore that created a strong public policy in California which would outlaw the choice of law provision, I don't know if I make myself.","start":442.436,"stop":479.709,"duration":37.27}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't see what are the arguments you make here about in effect Federal preemption, if they didn't prevail as you make them, why it would make it improper for California as a matter of public policy to reject New York law?","start":479.709,"stop":496.965,"duration":17.26}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I haven't said that, Your Honor, except that I want to make this point, the California statute which is Business and Professions Code 16,600, provides every contract by which anyone is restrained from engaging in a lawful profession trade or business of any kind, is to that extent void.","start":496.965,"stop":527.98,"duration":31.02},{"text":"That's what the statute says.","start":527.98,"stop":529.682,"duration":1.7},{"text":"Now the Supreme Court in this Muggill v. Reuben H. Donnelley, held that the application of that statute to a provision in a plan that was similar to this, would render this forfeiture clause, unenforceable in California.","start":529.682,"stop":553.34,"duration":23.66},{"text":"However, that statute doesn't mean what it says, because the Supreme Court of California in another case, Gordan against Wandell has said that statute will not apply in a situation where there are trade secrets or customers lists or things of that nature involve.","start":553.34,"stop":574.402,"duration":21.06},{"text":"That is, what we can fairly -- we think show here, if we get to arbitration, what we are asking here is our right to arbitrate.","start":574.402,"stop":586.316,"duration":11.91},{"text":"We have an agreement to arbitrate with Mr. Ware which is under the Federal Arbitration Act and under the State Arbitrate Act, a valid, irrevocable and enforceable.","start":586.316,"stop":603.984,"duration":17.67},{"text":"In addition to that we have --","start":603.984,"stop":605.795,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"But it's not enforceable under the State Arbitration Act.","start":605.795,"stop":608.642,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir.","start":608.642,"stop":609.322,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly it's not enforceable under the State Arbitration Act. Does it?","start":609.322,"stop":612.815,"duration":3.49},{"text":"Because the California Court of Appeal ruled against it?","start":612.815,"stop":617.416,"duration":4.6}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah, that's why we are here.","start":617.416,"stop":619.92,"duration":2.5},{"text":"We think it's clearly enforceable under the State Arbitration Act as it is under the Federal Act.","start":619.92,"stop":626.842,"duration":6.92},{"text":"And we think that otherwise, it would be a forum shopping as the Chief Judge Foll dealt with the (Inaudible) DeBerry case.","start":626.842,"stop":642.252,"duration":15.41},{"text":"But we are entitled to it under that, in addition Mr. Justice we are entitled to it under the New York Stock Exchange rules particularly 347B.","start":642.252,"stop":655.568,"duration":13.32},{"text":"Now these rules were promulgated pursuant to Section 6C of the Securities and Exchange Act of 1934 and they are in this industry, the only industry of its kind where this court has referred to it as federally mandated self-regulation.","start":655.568,"stop":679.735,"duration":24.17},{"text":"Arbitration is a very important part of that self-regulation and we have here a situation involving inter-state commerce and we have here a situation involving the question whether these rules, the New York Stock exchange will be uniformly applied, if we are in New York, for example, there's perfectly clear that there would be arbitration under the rules.","start":679.735,"stop":710.81,"duration":31.07},{"text":"So we think that we are entitled to arbitrate and entitled both under the Federal statute and under the rules of the Stock Exchange.","start":710.81,"stop":730.71,"duration":19.9}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What if this provision of the exchange rule was contrary to laws of New York?","start":730.71,"stop":738.234,"duration":7.52},{"text":"Let's assume that New York had a provision like California does or about this arbitration and this restrictive agreement.","start":738.234,"stop":750.917,"duration":12.68}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well the plan is to be interpreted under the laws of New York.","start":750.917,"stop":756.092,"duration":5.17},{"text":"Now, if New York had ruled it invalid, clearly the provision couldn't be interpreted in favor of Merrill Lynch.","start":756.092,"stop":765.039,"duration":8.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then are you saying that it's just the agreement in the contract that invalidates the California provision, or are you saying that there is provision in the Federal law, which says that the validity of the exchange rules is to be governed by the law of the state in which it is located?","start":765.039,"stop":789.421,"duration":24.38},{"text":"If some other state that attempts to invalidate what is consistent with New York law, the Federal law prevents.","start":789.421,"stop":801.134,"duration":11.71}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Federal law says in Section 6C that the Stock.Exchange shall adopt rules consistent with the rules of the state in which it is located and the New York Stock Exchange is located in New York and those rules are consonant with the laws of New York.","start":801.134,"stop":821.642,"duration":20.51}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And then you are arguing that if California, nevertheless attempts to invalidate a Stock Exchange rule which is consistent with the law of New York, it's the Federal law that prevents California from doing so.","start":821.642,"stop":833.982,"duration":12.34}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That why I think think the doctrine of preemption, it seems to me.","start":833.982,"stop":839.597,"duration":5.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the preemption that you called it, but it's a conflict in preemption?","start":839.597,"stop":843.187,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's quite exactly so, now I have an --","start":843.187,"stop":846.365,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Putting in an argument that is the conflict.","start":846.365,"stop":847.955,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes let me.","start":847.955,"stop":848.59,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Putting it in another way, Mr. Orrick.","start":848.59,"stop":850.409,"duration":1.82},{"text":"If I understand it correctly.","start":850.409,"stop":852.312,"duration":1.9},{"text":"What you are really arguing is that by reason of the Federal statute section C, that statute makes California law inapplicable to the determination of this issue.","start":852.312,"stop":866.016,"duration":13.7},{"text":"Only New York law maybe tested to see, whether New York law, or whether these regulations went consistent with New York law.","start":866.016,"stop":873.495,"duration":7.48}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct Mr. Justice and that now brings me to a discussion of the California Statute, Labor Code Section 224.","start":873.495,"stop":880.611,"duration":7.12}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well if you are right about that, what's left to the case?","start":880.611,"stop":885.114,"duration":4.5}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah arbitration.","start":885.114,"stop":887.063,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, No.","start":887.063,"stop":888.21,"duration":1.15},{"text":"But then you won your case on arbitration.","start":888.21,"stop":892.515,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah.","start":892.515,"stop":893.075,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean that's the only issue, thing that's here.","start":893.075,"stop":895.262,"duration":2.19},{"text":"The only issue that's here is arbitration.","start":895.262,"stop":897.02,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":897.02,"stop":898.087,"duration":1.07},{"text":"And then we go back to arbitrate.","start":898.087,"stop":900.554,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well actually I suppose, the issue is whether this California Statute was properly applied to deny arbitration.","start":900.554,"stop":908.559,"duration":8}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct and there are Mr. Justice, there are in effect two California Statute here in question.","start":908.559,"stop":917.671,"duration":9.11}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Whatever they may be if you are right and your interpretation of section C of the Federal Statute and of the Supremacy of the Federal Statute, as applied here, we don't have to get into any California Statute.","start":917.671,"stop":930.876,"duration":13.2}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Orrick, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":930.876,"stop":932.043,"duration":1.17},{"text":"May I reserved the rest of my time.","start":932.043,"stop":935.269,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":935.269,"stop":942.887,"duration":7.62},{"text":"Mr. Barton.","start":942.887,"stop":944.459,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Your Honor.","start":944.459,"stop":945.367,"duration":0.91},{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":945.367,"stop":949.585,"duration":4.22},{"text":"I think it's important for this case, perspective so that the court can consider that the narrow issues that are presented here.","start":949.585,"stop":958.613,"duration":9.03},{"text":"This case is really about 100 or more former employees of Merrill Lynch who resided in California.","start":958.613,"stop":967.725,"duration":9.11},{"text":"And who worked for their employer with integrity and with competency.","start":967.725,"stop":972.679,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"In California.","start":972.679,"stop":973.5,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"In California, right.","start":973.5,"stop":975.753,"duration":2.25},{"text":"And by reason of their employment and by reason of contributing to the success of Merill Lynch are entitled to be paid to earn wages.","start":975.753,"stop":985.93,"duration":10.18},{"text":"Now there is no dispute in this case that the profit-sharing that we are talking about is wages.","start":985.93,"stop":991.43,"duration":5.5}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"This was not a contributing plan, was it?","start":991.43,"stop":993.815,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, it was not.","start":993.815,"stop":996.479,"duration":2.66},{"text":"I believe petitioner stipulated to the definition of wages as authoritatively construed by the California Supreme Court in the case of Wise v. Southern Pacific.","start":996.479,"stop":1007.318,"duration":10.84},{"text":"So they are asking that they be paid their lawfully approved wages.","start":1007.318,"stop":1012.292,"duration":4.97},{"text":"Now this case is not about any individuals who have violated any rules of the New York Stock Exchange, any regulations of the Securities and Exchange Commission.","start":1012.292,"stop":1023.984,"duration":11.69}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"How do we know that, is there a record of evidence on that subject?","start":1023.984,"stop":1027.685,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"The determination of the class, Your Honor was limited to those individuals who by reason of one fact, they went to work with a competitor where they opened a competing business were denied their profit-sharing rights.","start":1027.685,"stop":1043.603,"duration":15.92},{"text":"There is nothing in the case.","start":1043.603,"stop":1044.501,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well under that, might not there be a showing that there was the use of customer list?","start":1044.501,"stop":1053.264,"duration":8.76}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I believe that the interpretation of Business and Professions Code Section 16,600 forecloses that consideration because it states on its very face that any restraint, and there is a different set of laws Your Honor in California that applied to customer lists and confidential information.","start":1053.264,"stop":1077.516,"duration":24.25}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well that's the question that whether a contract clause fixing the forum and calling for arbitration is valid.","start":1077.516,"stop":1087.761,"duration":10.24},{"text":"Isn't that what this case is?","start":1087.761,"stop":1090.934,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well Your Honor.","start":1090.934,"stop":1092.325,"duration":1.39},{"text":"Yes, that is correct.","start":1092.325,"stop":1094.635,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's actually a question whether it can be enforced against the will of the forum state.","start":1094.635,"stop":1099.501,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't think that's the question Your Honor.","start":1099.501,"stop":1103.173,"duration":3.67},{"text":"Arbitration is not mandated by any rule of the Securities and Exchange Commission as amicus has pointed out in this brief nor is it required by any--","start":1103.173,"stop":1113.206,"duration":10.03}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Stock Exchange Commission.","start":1113.206,"stop":1117.032,"duration":3.83}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Securities and Exchange Commission has filed amicus brief in the case and it's their position that the rule is not required by any regulation, any legislations enacted by Congress in the Securities and Exchange Act particularly and it's not required by any rule or regulations promulgated by the Securities and Exchange Commission.","start":1117.032,"stop":1139.301,"duration":22.27}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"This argument arose in New York, I suppose the other things with the clause would have been enforced wouldn't it?","start":1139.301,"stop":1145.889,"duration":6.59}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well Your Honor, you are asking about a question about New York law.","start":1145.889,"stop":1148.356,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I am.","start":1148.356,"stop":1149.077,"duration":0.72},{"text":"Yes.","start":1149.077,"stop":1149.697,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well and according to the case that I have cited to my brief.","start":1149.697,"stop":1152.946,"duration":3.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I will ask it in another way then.","start":1152.946,"stop":1154.769,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"It would not have been enforced Your Honor, because it concerns a matter of illegality which is unenforceable in the New York Courts pursuant to the decision of the highest court, the Court of Appeals.","start":1154.769,"stop":1165.538,"duration":10.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I will ask you in another way.","start":1165.538,"stop":1168.835,"duration":3.3},{"text":"Your position in the case is that California law governs this case as to the enforceability of the arbitration.","start":1168.835,"stop":1177.275,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1177.275,"stop":1181.494,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Why isn't New York law applicable?","start":1181.494,"stop":1184.261,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Why is it New York law because the number one, Your Honor, the case was submitted to the California Courts based on California law by the petitioner and the petitioner asked for interpretation of the RE 1 form and Rule 347B.","start":1184.261,"stop":1201.93,"duration":17.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Who brought the lawsuit?","start":1201.93,"stop":1203.776,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1203.776,"stop":1205.858,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And you based it on New York, on California law.","start":1205.858,"stop":1209.18,"duration":3.32}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the nexus of the compliant Your Honor, was about the forfeiture provision in a profit-sharing plan which has nothing to do with the securities.","start":1209.18,"stop":1215.855,"duration":6.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the case was decided by the court on the basis of California law.","start":1215.855,"stop":1219.835,"duration":3.98},{"text":"Wasn't it?","start":1219.835,"stop":1220.609,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct, Your Honor.","start":1220.609,"stop":1221.94,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And the court below applied California law.","start":1221.94,"stop":1225.297,"duration":3.36}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it did Your Honor, as to one little area.","start":1225.297,"stop":1229.55,"duration":4.25},{"text":"We have got an exception.","start":1229.55,"stop":1230.805,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the area is whether or not the arbitration clauses to be enforced in this case?","start":1230.805,"stop":1236.056,"duration":5.25}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well that's the specific question but the general question.","start":1236.056,"stop":1238.83,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I just.","start":1238.83,"stop":1239.407,"duration":0.58},{"text":"I don't want to go any farther than that.","start":1239.407,"stop":1240.972,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes that's correct.","start":1240.972,"stop":1241.633,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I am talking about the arbitration provision.","start":1241.633,"stop":1243.378,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"As to wage dispute.","start":1243.378,"stop":1244.858,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The California law governed this, it was helping to govern this case.","start":1244.858,"stop":1249.541,"duration":4.68}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct Your Honor.","start":1249.541,"stop":1250.669,"duration":1.13},{"text":"As to wage disputes.","start":1250.669,"stop":1252.618,"duration":1.95},{"text":"Yes.","start":1252.618,"stop":1253.775,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now let's assume that the arbitration clause was quite valid in New York.","start":1253.775,"stop":1259.47,"duration":5.69}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Was valid in New York.","start":1259.47,"stop":1260.756,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's assume that it was.","start":1260.756,"stop":1262.435,"duration":1.68},{"text":"Now 6C says that the Stock Exchange rule, Stock Exchange may make rule, consistent with the law of state which they are incorporated in.","start":1262.435,"stop":1274.61,"duration":12.17}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct Your Honor.","start":1274.61,"stop":1275.469,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Now why should California be able to apply its law when the Federal law says the exchange rules are to be tested thereby, the law of the state in which it is located.","start":1275.469,"stop":1287.165,"duration":11.7}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me, Your Honor.","start":1287.165,"stop":1287.976,"duration":0.81},{"text":"There has been no definition yet in legislative history of the Act of what located means.","start":1287.976,"stop":1293.916,"duration":5.94},{"text":"Now I submit Your Honor, that New York Stock Exchange is physically located in New York.","start":1293.916,"stop":1299.167,"duration":5.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's assume that we decided here or some court decided that located means for the New York Stock Exchange, it means New York.","start":1299.167,"stop":1308.333,"duration":9.17},{"text":"Let's assume that.","start":1308.333,"stop":1309.181,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":1309.181,"stop":1310.051,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's assume it for purposes of Section 6C, the Stock Exchange is located in New York then what?","start":1310.051,"stop":1317.545,"duration":7.49}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"As the matter would be decided under New York state law, New York state law would determine where the arbitration would---","start":1317.545,"stop":1324.621,"duration":7.08}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Contrary to what was the law that was applied in this case?","start":1324.621,"stop":1331.078,"duration":6.46}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe that New York state law is contrary in outcome, I believe it would be the same result.","start":1331.078,"stop":1335.521,"duration":4.44}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we will resume at that point after lunch.","start":1335.521,"stop":1339.12,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph C. Barton","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Your Honor.","start":1339.12,"stop":1342.01,"duration":2.89}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Oct  9 - 10, 1973","petitioner":"Merrill Lynch, Pierce, Fenner & Smith, Inc.","respondent":"Ware","docket":"72-312","citation":"414 US 117 (1973)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/414/117","lowerCourt":"Supreme Court of California","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Dec 4, 1973"}